					<h3 class="subtituloPost">Modules</h3>
					<p class="paragrafoPost">
						ERP is usually divided in two modules, which means two ways 
						to see it, department and segment. In the department view, 
						we have the accounting, financial, buyers, etc. In this view 
						can be seen all the process of each department in the same screen. 
						It makes the management easier to the user, as so we don`t have 
						people from outside of the payment list seeing those information, 
						as well as the production employees can’t see the financial area. 
						The segmentation view, unlike the department view, shows only one 
						process of the segmentation. As an example, a transportation 
						enterprise has a process aiming just their activities, unlike 
						a school, that will have the capability to control the absences. 
						The module with the department view has standard routines that 
						hardly changes from one enterprise to another.
					</p>

					<h3 class="subtituloPost">Objectives</h3>
					<p class="paragrafoPost">
						The goal of the ERP is to organize the work in an enterprise. 
						This happens storing information from the clients, employees, 
						products etc and making they have a relation. The ERP then 
						integrates the processes based on rules pre-established by the 
						company to serve as daily tasks for employees of the company.
					</p>

					<h3 class="subtituloPost">Benefits</h3>
					<p class="paragrafoPost">
						The benefits of adopting the ERP system can be tangible or intangible. Thus, we can quote:
						
						<ul class="paragrafoPost">
							<li>Cost reduction related with material waste and labor;</li>
							<li>Process automation;</li>
							<li>Sorter delivery time;</li>
							<li>IT cost reduction</li>
							<li>Increase revenue and profit.</li>
						</ul>
					</p>
						
					<p class="paragrafoPost">
						To the intangible ones we have:

						<ul class="paragrafoPost">
							<li>Tax management with lower risk of fine;</li>
							<li>Better communication between sectors;</li>
							<li>Better use of the managers’ time;</li>
							<li>Help in decision making;</li>
							<li>Improvement in costumers’ relationship.</li>
						</ul>
					</p>
					
					</br>
					
					<p class="paragrafoPost">
						<strong>
							Therefore, the ERP is responsible for organizing your company. Being an indispensable tool to manage the growth of your business.
						</strong>
					</p>
